[CLAIM]
While no significant baseline difference in personality traits and moral decision tendency were found across two groups of participants, our analyses revealed that social observation promoted deontological judgments especially for moral dilemmas involving direct bodily harm (i.e., personal moral dilemmas), yet with an overall decrease in decision confidence and significant prolongation of reaction time. we found a significant interaction effect between the group and dilemma type, F(1.742, 80.11) = 4.779, p = .014, partial eta squared = 0.094

[HYPOTHESIS]
Social observation will induce deontological decision bias in the context of moral dilemmas, meaning those told they are being observed will make a higher proportion of deontological judgements, especially for moral dilemmas involving direct bodily harm (i.e., personal moral dilemmas)
